Graphical Exploration

Q1-4

Q1:

The relationship between body mass and length seems positively linear but some data points (may be outlier) are grouping outside of the linear trend.

Q2:

The spread of the frequency of the body mass is near to the normal distribution. But it slightly right skew. The body length is also significantly right skewed.

Q3:

According to the histograms and Shapiro normality tests, the unconditioned body masses and body length are not normally distributed. The p value is <0.05 and thus reject the null hypothesis that the data points are normally distributed. On the other hand, visually, the histograms are both showing evidence of right skew.

Q4:

According to the boxplots, the Delomys dorsalis is heavier than the D. sublineatus. Similarly, the male Delomys sp. are heavier than the female Delomys sp. When considering the interaction between both species and sex body mass, the male D. dorsalis is heaviest and lightest is the female D. sublineatus. Within species the males are heavier than the females.

Model Diagnostics

fit1<-lm(body_length~body_mass, data=delomys)
  
fit2<-lm(body_mass~sex, data=delomys)

fit3<-lm(body_mass~binomial, data=delomys)

fit4<-lm(body_mass~sex+binomial, data=delomys)

fit5<-lm(body_mass~sex*binomial, data=delomys)

Histograms model residuals

hist(residuals(fit1))

hist(residuals(fit2))

hist(residuals(fit3))

hist(residuals(fit4))

hist(residuals(fit5))

Shapiro test model residuals

Q5-6

Q5:

The graphical diagnostics of the histogram of the residuals seems to be normally distributed. However, according to the numerical diagnostics, the residuals are not normally-distributed (lower p value in shapiro test).

Q6:

The most violations of normality are found in the fit1 model, least severe for the fit2 model. And the fit3, fit4 and fit5 models are about equal violation.

Model Interpretation are we supposed to do all of the models?

Q7-9

Q7:

The magnitude of the mass/length relationship is that with every one unit increase in length, the mass is predicted to be increased about 0.88 units.

Q8:

For an animal that weighs 100 g the expected length is 76.1246565+(100*0.875)= 163.62

Q9:

The expected body length of an animal that weighs 0g is 76.12. (But in reality, zero body mass means zero body length.)
